[3] USA (New York)
Date: Sun 17 Jul 2022 12:24 PM EDT
Source: Times Union [abridged, edited]
https://www.timesunion.com/news/article/In-5-days-monkeypox-cases-double-in-New-York-17310538.php


As of Friday [15 Jul 2022], New York confirmed 490 cases of monkeypox in people -- compared with 238 on Monday, 11 Jul 2022.

Most of the cases have been in New York City's 5 boroughs. However, there were new cases identified upstate as of Friday [15 Jul 2022] -- one each in Erie, Monroe, and St Lawrence counties. Other counties that have had confirmed cases are Chemung, Nassau, Rockland, Suffolk, Sullivan, and Westchester.

State reporting to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention can lag behind real-time data. But as of Friday [15 Jul 2022], New York almost had twice as many cases as the state with the 2nd most confirmed illnesses, California.

Nassau, Suffolk, Saratoga, and Westchester counties are the only counties outside New York City where the state is providing a vaccine. Last week, only about 1/3 of available monkeypox vaccine in Saratoga County was given to people who had made appointments at 2 private clinic times.

Saratoga County, which has had no confirmed cases, said in a release last week that it is being given monkeypox vaccine because of its status as a "tourist" destination. The information did not mention the Saratoga Race Course. However, the track's summer meet, as well as associated events and parties, started Thursday [14 Jul 2022].

Saratoga's health department webpage as of Sunday [17 Jan 2022] did not indicate when more vaccine clinics will be held. The county was initially slated to receive 300 doses to be used for the 1st of the 2-shot regiment. On Tuesday [12 Jul 2022], the state announced Saratoga will get another 620 doses, both to be used for the 2nd shot of the regimen, and for providing vaccine to new patients.

[byline: Lauren Stanforth]

